AMENDED AND RESTATED SUBSTATION USE AGREEMENT by and between IRONWOOD WINDPOWER, LLC and WESTAR ENERGY, INC.
dated as of November 17, 2016
AMENDED AND RESTATED SUBSTATION USE AGREEMENT This Amended and Restated Substation Use Agreement ("Agreement") is entered into as of November 17, 2016 by and between WESTAR ENERGY, INC., a Kansas corporation ("Westar"), and IRONWOOD WINDPOWER, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company organized under the laws of Delaware ("Ironwood"). RECITALS A. Each of the Parties have developed, or will develop, wind electricity generation projects on certain real property in Ford County, Kansas. B. Each Party holds its own individual real property rights (by fee ownership, lease, easement, right of way, or otherwise) to the real property associated with its respective Facility (as defined herein) and its respective facilities within the Substation (as defined herein). C. The Parties wish to set forth herein their respective rights and obligations regarding the joint use, maintenance, repair, replacement of, and additions with respect to the Shared Substation Facilities (as defined herein). D. The Parties entered into the Substation Use Agreement dated as of August 22, 2016 (the "Original Agreement") which set forth the rights and obligations of the Parties with respect to the Shared Substation Facilities. E. The Parties wish to amend and restate the Original Agreement on the terms and subject to the conditions set forth herein. AGREEMENT NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises contained herein and other good and valuable consideration, Ironwood and Westar agree as follows: Article 1
DEFINITIONS 1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, the following terms shall have the respective meanings set forth below. Certain other capitalized terms are defined where they appear in this Agreement. "Affiliate" of any named Person means any Person that controls, is under the control of, or is under common control with, the named Person. The term "control" (including the terms "controls," "under the control of" and "under common control with") means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management and policies of a Person, whether through ownership interest, by contract or otherwise. For purposes of this definition of Affiliate, the direct or indirect ownership of fifty percent (50%) or more of the outstanding capital stock or other equity interests of any Person having ordinary voting power shall be deemed to be "control." "Aggregate ITC Substation Delivered Energy" has the meaning set forth in Section 3.4. "Aggregate Substation Delivered Energy" has the meaning set forth in Section 3.4. "Agreement" has the meaning set forth in the introductory paragraph hereof. "Alternate" has the meaning set forth in Section 3.10. "Authorized Representative" has the meaning set forth in Section 3.10. "Business Day" means any calendar day that is not a Saturday, a Sunday, a holiday on which banks in the State of Kansas are permitted to close, or a NERC recognized holiday. "Commercial Operation Date" means the date that Westar provides written notice to Ironwood that the Westar Facility is physically complete, commissioned and fully operational and capable of continuous operation. "Delivered Energy" means all of the electricity generated by each Facility and delivered to either (i) the Substation, as measured at the applicable Metering Point for each Facility, or (ii) the ITC Substation, as measured at the ITC Metering Point. "Dispute" has the meaning set forth in Section 9.1. "Dispute Notice" has the meaning set forth in Section 9.1. "Effective Date" has the meaning set forth in Section 2.1.. "Event of Default" has the meaning set forth in Section 5.1. "Expiration Date" has the meaning set forth in Section 2.1. "Facilities" means, collectively, the Westar Facility and the Ironwood Facility and "Facility" means, individually, the Westar Facility or the Ironwood Facility, as applicable. "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor thereto. "Force Majeure Event" has the meaning set forth in Section 7.1. "Good Utility Practice(s)" means the practices, methods, and acts that would be implemented and followed by a prudent operator of relevant facilities similar to the facilities in question in the United States during the relevant time period, which practices, methods and acts, in the exercise of prudent and responsible professional judgment in light of the facts known or that should reasonably have been known at the time a decision was made, would reasonably have been expected to accomplish the desired result in a manner consistent with good business practices, Requirements of Law, applicable standards, (including any applicable SPP and NERC requirements), equipment manufacturer's recommendations, reliability, safety, environmental protection, economy and expedition. "Indemnified Party" has the meaning set forth in Section 7.4.1. "Indemnifying Party" has the meaning set forth in Section 7.4.1. "Ironwood" has the meaning set forth in the introductory paragraph hereof. "Ironwood Facility" means that certain 167.9 MW wind electricity generation project known as the Ironwood wind project located in Ford County, Kansas constructed and operated by Ironwood. "Ironwood Substation Facilities" means the facilities and equipment identified in Schedule 2 of this Agreement as being the "Duke Substation Facilities" that are owned, maintained and operated by Ironwood and that form part of the Substation. "ITC Metering Point" means the location where energy generated by the Facilities and previously collected at the Substation and transferred to the ITC Substation is measured in connection with determining total output of Delivered Energy from each Facility. "ITC Substation" means that substation identified in Schedule 2 as being the "ITC Substation" that, among other functions, is used to transmit power from the Facilities as initially collected at the Substation to the electrical grid. "Losses" means losses, costs, expenses, liabilities, damages, fines, and penalties, including court costs, reasonable attorneys' and professionals' fees and expenses, and other litigation or settlement expenses. "Metering Equipment" means the physical equipment and any related software used to measure the total output of (i) Delivered Energy from each Facility at the Metering Points, or (ii) Delivered Energy from the Substation at the ITC Metering Point, as described in further detail in Schedule 2. "Metering Points" means the locations where energy generated by each Facility is measured in connection with determining total output of Delivered Energy, as such location are identified in Schedule 1 attached hereto. "NERC" means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation or any successor organization. "Operating Protocol" means the operating protocols to be developed by the Parties with respect to the method for day to day communications, method for communicating access to the relevant facilities, telecommunications and data acquisition procedures, key personnel list for applicable Westar and Ironwood operating centers, and such other matters as may be mutually agreed upon by the Parties. "Party" and "Parties," means in the singular, either Ironwood or Westar, and in the plural both Ironwood and Westar. "Party Representative" and "Parties' Representatives" have the meaning set forth in Section 9.1. "Person" means any individual, entity, corporation, general or limited partnership, limited liability company, joint venture, estate, trust, association or other entity or governmental authority. "Power Purchase Agreement" means that certain Renewable Energy Purchase Agreement, dated as of December 9, 2010, by and between Westar and Ironwood, as amended, modified or supplemented from time to time. "Representatives" of a Party mean any Affiliates, directors, officers, employees, agents or controlling persons of such person, and the consultants and legal counsel of such Party. "Requirements of Law" means any federal, state and local law, statute, regulation, rule, code or ordinance enacted, adopted, issued or promulgated by any federal, state, local or other governmental authority or regulatory body (including those pertaining to electrical, building, zoning, environmental and occupational safety and health requirements). "Shared Substation Facilities" means (a) approximately 200 feet of 3-phase 345 kV high bus, (b) one 3-phase horizontal throw 345 kV F-type motor operated disconnect switch, (c) 150 feet of 3-phase overhead conductor, (d) structural steel, and (e) supports and insulators which are part of the Substation which are identified in Schedule 2 as being the "Shared Substation Facilities" that will be co-owned with Ironwood and Westar each owning a 50% undivided ownership interest in such Shared Substation Facilities. The "Shared Substation Facilities" will be operated, maintained and repaired by Ironwood, and used by both Parties to deliver energy from the Facilities to the ITC Substation for transmission to the electric grid and includes the dedicated facilities leaving the Substation that are required to transmit energy generated by the Facilities from the Substation to the ITC Substation (up to and before the breaker located in the ITC Substation) for transmission to the electric grid. "SPP" means the Southwest Power Pool, Inc., or its successor as to any function. "Substation" means that substation detailed in Schedule 2, that, among other functions, is used to step up power from the Facilities to transmission voltage and to deliver Delivered Energy to the ITC Substation and ultimately the electrical grid. "System Emergency" means any condition or situation that in the commercially reasonable judgment of any Party (i) is imminently likely to endanger life, property or the environment or (ii) is imminently likely to cause a material adverse effect on the security of or damage to the Substation or the systems to which the Substation is directly or indirectly connected. "Term" shall mean the period commencing on the Effective Date and continuing until the Expiration Date. "Westar" has the meaning set forth in the introductory paragraph hereof. "Westar Facility" means that certain 280.6 MW wind electricity generation project known as the Western Plains wind project located in Ford County, Kansas to be constructed and operated by Westar. "Westar Substation Facilities" means the facilities and equipment identified in Schedule 2 of this Agreement as being the "Westar Substation Facilities" that are to be constructed and paid for by Westar and will be owned, maintained and operated by Westar and which form part of the Substation. 1.2 Rules of Interpretation. For purposes of this Agreement, except where otherwise expressly provided or unless the context otherwise necessarily requires: 1.2.1 references to this Agreement shall include a reference to all appendices, annexes, schedules and exhibits hereto, as the same may be amended, modified, supplemented or replaced from time to time; 1.2.2 the words "herein," "hereof," "hereunder" and "herewith" shall refer to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular section or subsection of this Agreement; 1.2.3 the terms "include," "includes" and "including" shall be construed to mean "including, without limitation" or "including but not limited to" and shall not be construed to mean that the examples given are an exclusive list of the topics covered; 1.2.4 references to "Articles," "Sections," "Schedules" or "Exhibits" shall be to articles, sections, schedules or exhibits (if any) of this Agreement; 1.2.5 references to a given agreement, instrument or other document shall be a reference to that agreement, instrument or other document as modified, amended, supplemented and restated through the date as of which such reference is made; 1.2.6 references to a Person include its successors and permitted assigns; 1.2.7 the singular shall include the plural and the masculine shall include the feminine and neuter and vice versa; and 1.2.8 reference to a given Requirement of Law is a reference to that Requirement of Law and the Requirements of Law adopted or promulgated thereunder, in each case, as amended, modified, supplemented or restated as of the date on which the reference is made. Article 2
TERM 2.1 Term. This Agreement shall become effective as of the date upon which this Agreement is deemed accepted for filing as a rate schedule by FERC (the "Effective Date") and shall continue until the first occurrence of: (a) retirement or abandonment of both Facilities or (b) termination of this Agreement under Section 5.2 (such date, the "Expiration Date"). Upon the retirement or abandonment of either the Ironwood Facility or the Westar Facility the non-retiring or abandoning Party shall have the right to purchase the other Party's remaining interest in the Shared Substation Facilities at fair market value and on terms and conditions mutually agreed upon by the Parties. Ironwood shall give at least one hundred eighty (180) days prior written notice of the retirement or abandonment of the Ironwood Facility. Upon the retirement or abandonment of the Westar Facility, Westar shall dismantle and remove any Westar Substation Facilities located on real property held by Ironwood. Such removal shall be in accordance with reasonable instructions provided to Westar by Ironwood so that any removal satisfies the requirements of the applicable real property rights associated with such real property. Article 3
SUBSTATION FACILITIES 3.1 Substation Use and Alteration. Subject to this Section 3.1, in order for Westar to connect to the Shared Substation Facilities, Ironwood shall permit the construction of the Westar Substation Facilities within the Substation. Westar agrees to use its interest in the Shared Substation Facilities for delivery of power and energy from the Westar Facility in an amount not to exceed 330 MW; provided that such limitation shall not apply if Westar develops and constructs one or more separate wind electricity generation projects and Westar and Ironwood (or their respective Affiliates) agree upon mutually acceptable terms and conditions regarding such Substation use. Westar, at its sole cost and expense, shall construct and install the Westar Substation Facilities in accordance with the design specifications mutually agreed to by Westar and Ironwood and shall coordinate any disconnection or de-energization of the Ironwood Substation Facilities with Ironwood. As a condition to connection of the Westar Facility to the Shared Substation Facilities, Westar shall reimburse Ironwood all of the third party costs and expenses incurred by Ironwood in connection with the accommodation of Westar's request to connect and utilize the Shared Substation Facilities, including legal fees associated with the negotiation and execution of this Agreement and professional, consultant or engineering fees associated with design and engineering review performed by or on behalf of Ironwood in connection with this Agreement; provided that Westar shall not be required to reimburse Ironwood for any such costs or expenses in excess of Sixty Thousand Dollars ($60,000). Prior to connecting the Westar Facility to, or utilizing, the Shared Substation Facilities, Ironwood shall issue an invoice to Westar for such costs and expenses. Westar shall pay the invoice for such costs and expenses prior to commencing the use of the Shared Substation Facilities or connecting the Westar Facility to the Shared Substation Facilities. Westar shall not commence construction on any real property held by Ironwood until after it has provided Ironwood with at least thirty (30) days of advance written notice stating the date on which Westar intends to commence such work. Westar shall compensate Ironwood for all lost revenues, including grossed up production tax credits, of Ironwood that result from lost generation due to disconnection of the Ironwood Facility during the construction and connection of the Westar Substation Facilities. If the disconnection for the construction and connection of the Westar Substation Facilities occurs during a scheduled maintenance outage of the Ironwood Facility, Westar shall only be obligated to compensate Ironwood for lost revenues and grossed up tax credits to the extent that such disconnection exceeds the actual time period required for the performance of the scheduled maintenance work for the Ironwood Facility. If Westar is obligated to compensate Ironwood under this Section 3.1, Westar shall compensate Ironwood in accordance with Section 8.01(b) of the Power Purchase Agreement without regard to whether Westar actually directed Ironwood to curtail energy pursuant to Section 7.04 of the Power Purchase Agreement. 3.2 Current Description of Substation Facilities. The Ironwood Substation Facilities as described in Schedule 2 enable Ironwood to receive energy produced by the Ironwood Facility at the Substation, and deliver the energy onto the utility transmission system at the ITC Substation. Upon completion of the Westar Substation Facilities, the Substation shall be capable of receiving energy produced by the Westar Facility, and delivering the energy onto the utility transmission system at the ITC Substation. 3.3 Ownership and Operation of the Substation Facilities & Additional Use. Subject at all times to each Party's obligations under this Agreement, including under Section 3.1, current and future Ironwood Substation Facilities shall at all times remain the property of Ironwood, and the Westar Substation Facilities shall at all times remain the property of Westar. As set forth in Section 3.5, the Parties shall at all times operate and maintain the portion of the Substation over which it has all right, title and interest, consistent with Good Utility Practice, Requirements of Law and the Power Purchase Agreement, and shall restore the connection of each of the Ironwood Substation Facilities and Westar Substation Facilities, as applicable, to the Substation as soon as practicable when interruptions occur. Subject at all times to the other Party's advanced written consent, which may be granted or withheld in its sole discretion, either Party shall have the right to (a) modify the then existing Shared Substation Facilities or construct new facilities as it deems necessary to receive and deliver Delivered Energy; or (b) modify the Shared Substation Facilities to attach third party facilities. The modifying Party shall provide written notice to the other Party of any such proposed modification or addition at least one-hundred twenty (120) days prior to commencing any change. Any Party installing additional facilities on the Shared Substation Facilities or modifying any Shared Substation Facilities shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Party from all Losses, including third party claims, property and revenue losses incurred, including grossed up production tax credits, as a result of such construction or installation activities, to the extent such claims and damages are not covered by the insurance required by Section 3.11. If Westar is obligated to compensate Ironwood pursuant to this Section 3.3, and the Power Purchase Agreement has not expired or been terminated, Westar shall compensate Ironwood in accordance with Section 8.01(b) of the Power Purchase Agreement (without regard to whether Westar actually directed Ironwood to curtail energy pursuant to Section 7.04 of the Power Purchase Agreement) to the extent any disconnection of the Shared Substation Facilities exceeds the actual time period required for the performance of the scheduled maintenance work for the Ironwood Facility during which such disconnection occurred. 3.4 Metering. All energy delivered from the Facilities to the Substation and delivered thereby to the ITC Substation shall be metered on a real-time basis at both the Metering Points and the ITC Metering Point. All Metering Equipment associated with the Metering Points for the Westar Facility (other than the ITC Metering Point) shall be installed by Westar at its sole cost and expense. The method, ownership structure and allocation of maintenance obligations to meter Delivered Energy from the Ironwood Facility shall be as set forth in Schedule 3. The Metering Equipment for metering the Delivered Energy from the Westar Facility shall be owned and maintained by Westar. The Metering Equipment for the ITC Metering Point shall be owned and maintained by a third party. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the amount of Delivered Energy attributable to each of the Facilities (including determining the amount of "Renewable Energy" delivered by Ironwood pursuant to Power Purchase Agreement) shall be determined in accordance with the methodology set forth in Schedule 3. 3.5 Access, Operation and Maintenance. Ironwood shall be responsible for the operation and maintenance, and any associated costs, of the Ironwood Substation Facilities. Westar shall be responsible for the operation and maintenance, and any associated costs, of the Westar Substation Facilities. Ironwood shall be responsible for the operation and maintenance of the Shared Substation Facilities. Ironwood and Westar shall share all costs and expenses (other than de minimis costs and expenses or costs and expenses associated with the general upkeep of the Substation but not solely pertaining to the Shared Substation Facilities) associated with the operation and maintenance of the Shared Substation Facilities on a 50/50 basis. Any maintenance on the Substation undertaken by a Party shall be completed in a timely fashion and in a manner consistent with Good Utility Practices and Requirements of Law. 3.5.1 Each Party and its Representatives shall have access to the Shared Substation Facilities (a) for inspection, (b) for any required maintenance of the Shared Substation Facilities agreed to be undertaken in accordance with this Agreement, (c) for repairs of the Shared Substation Facilities, and (d) for the operation of the Shared Substation Facilities, all in accordance with this Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, except in the event of a System Emergency, each Party shall provide no less than twenty-four (24) hours' prior notice to the other Party of its intent to access the Shared Substation Facilities and no less than forty-eight (48) hours' prior notice to the other Party prior to performing any maintenance or repairs pursuant to this Section 3.5.1, Section 3.5.2 or Section 3.7.2. In the event of a System Emergency, either Party may immediately access the Shared Substation Facilities without advanced notice to the other Party, provided that such accessing Party shall provide notice of its access, the type of System Emergency, and any actions undertaken to address the System Emergency as soon as practicable following the same. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, Ironwood shall not be required to provide notice to Westar of its intent to access the Ironwood Substation Facilities, unless such access involves maintenance or repair to the Shared Substation Facilities, and Westar shall not be required to provide notice to Ironwood of its intent to access the Westar Substation Facilities, unless in either case such access involves maintenance or repair to the Shared Substation Facilities, in which case notice shall be provided as set forth in this Section 3.5.1. A Party and or any Party's Representatives shall follow all applicable safety, security and site rules mutually agreed to by the Parties and shall comply with all applicable agreements (including the Power Purchase Agreement) and Requirements of Law when at the Substation. 3.5.2 In the event of a System Emergency, should maintenance on the Substation become necessary to ensure the efficient and proper operation of the Substation and the Party responsible for performing such maintenance fails to timely perform such maintenance the Party not responsible for such maintenance may perform, or cause to be performed, such maintenance, and the Party not performing such maintenance shall be responsible for all reasonable costs and expenses incurred by the Party performing such maintenance. 3.5.3 A Party's use of the Substation or the operation of its Facility may not interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Party of their respective rights in the Substation or the operation of their Facilities, except as specifically provided herein. No Party will permit its use of the Substation to create waste or nuisance, or jeopardize the issuance or maintenance of any insurance policy relating to the Facilities or any governmental approval. 3.6 Assistance with Interconnection Facility Inspections. Westar shall provide assistance to Ironwood, either directly or by causing any of its contractors to assist Ironwood, generally for Ironwood's inspections of the Westar Substation Facilities. Similarly, Ironwood shall provide assistance to Westar, either directly or by causing any of its contractors to assist Westar, generally for Westar's inspections of the Ironwood Substation Facilities. 3.7 Interruptions. 3.7.1 Notwithstanding any provision to the contrary, each Party reserves the right to disconnect, curtail or suspend the energization of the electrical connection of the Shared Substation Facilities without prior notice on a temporary basis to the extent necessary in the event of (i) a System Emergency, (ii) a Force Majeure Event, or (iii) a direction from any regulator or other governing agency with jurisdiction over the Substation. 3.7.2 Each Party reserves the right to disconnect, curtail or suspend the energization of the electrical connection of the Shared Substation Facilities for routine maintenance and in connection with construction of any additional facilities within the Substation that impacts the Substation. The Party intending to cause such interruption shall provide at least thirty (30) days' notice of such interruption in advance to the other Party. Any disconnection, curtailment or suspension of the energization and any maintenance of the Shared Substation Facilities shall be implemented as mutually agreed to by the Parties. 3.7.3 Each Party shall limit the duration of any interruptions occurring pursuant to Section 3.7.2, and shall promptly notify the other Party of the occurrence of any unintended interruptions, as soon as is practicable, and in no event later than twelve (12) hours after the commencement thereof, which notice shall give full particulars of the event causing such interruption, including the expected duration of the suspension or interruption. 3.7.4 To the extent any Party's operating Facilities are disconnected, or its ability to use the Shared Substation Facilities is adversely impacted or an outage occurs resulting in a loss of production and revenue to a Party's Facility, and the disconnection, adverse impact or outage is caused by the other Party's exercise of rights under Section 3.5 or Section 3.7.2, the responsible Party shall reimburse the Party which suffered the Loss within thirty (30) days of notice and supporting documentation of the Loss; provided that in the case when Ironwood is the Party suffering the Loss, if the Power Purchase Agreement has not expired or been terminated, Westar shall compensate Ironwood in accordance with Section 8.01(b) of the Power Purchase Agreement without regard to whether Westar actually directed Ironwood to curtail energy pursuant to Section 7.04 of the Power Purchase Agreement. 3.8 Obligations for Maintaining Connection to Metering Point. Except as specified herein and subject to the terms and conditions of the Power Purchase Agreement, each Party shall be responsible for all costs associated with moving power from its Facility to the Substation. 3.8.1 Westar will operate, maintain and control during the Term, at Westar's sole cost and expense, all of the Westar Substation Facilities, including all of the Westar Substation Facility's electrical equipment necessary to deliver energy to the Substation at its Metering Point. This equipment shall include such protective and regulating devices as are identified by Requirements of Law and required to be located on the Westar Facility's portion of the Substation, or as are otherwise necessary in accordance with Good Utility Practice to protect personnel and equipment and to minimize harmful effects to the Substation and Shared Substation Facilities. 3.8.2 Ironwood will operate, maintain and control during the Term, at Ironwood's sole cost and expense, all of the Ironwood Substation Facilities. This equipment shall include such protective and regulating devices as are identified by Requirements of Law, or as are otherwise necessary in accordance with Good Utility Practice to protect personnel and equipment and to minimize harmful effects to the Shared Substation Facilities. 3.8.3 Should any electrical connection requirement or electrical system reliability requirement of any regulatory authority, require that modifications be made to the Shared Substation Facilities for which cost is not reimbursed by such regulatory authority, Ironwood shall implement and be responsible for the costs of such modifications, and shall bill Westar for half of the costs of such modifications. 3.9 Standard of Operation. Ironwood shall operate its Facility in accordance with the terms of this Agreement, including all applicable Requirements of Law, Good Utility Practices and the Power Purchase Agreement. Westar shall operate its Facility in accordance with the terms of this Agreement, including all applicable Requirements of Law and Good Utility Practices. No Party will take any action, omit to take any action or fail to perform any obligation under this Agreement or any other relevant agreement that materially and adversely affects the other Party or the other Party's Facility or gives rise to a Loss affecting the other Party, the other Party's Facility or the Shared Substation Facilities, including any action, omission or failure to perform an obligation that results in damage to, disconnection of, or an outage of the other Party's Facility. 3.10 Operating Protocol; Authorized Representatives. No later than thirty (30) days before Westar intends to intertie the Westar Substation Facilities to the Shared Substation Facilities, the Parties shall develop and agree upon the Operating Protocol. Each Party has designated an authorized representative (an "Authorized Representative") and an alternate (an "Alternate") to act in the Authorized Representative's absence, with respect to the administration of the Operating Protocol. A Party's appointment of an Authorized Representative and Alternate shall remain in full force and effect until the Party delivers written notice of substitution to the other Party. The Authorized Representatives and Alternates shall have experience with asset management and with regard to matters relating to the implementation of the Parties' rights and obligations under this Agreement, with full authority to act for and on behalf of the Parties appointing them. 3.11 Insurance. For the duration of this Agreement, the Parties shall, at their sole cost and expense, maintain insurance policies and coverages for its respective facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practices. 3.12 Liens. No Party shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or permit to exist any lien on the Shared Substation Facilities or the property of the other Party, including any lien for unpaid taxes, any judgment lien or any mechanic's or materialmen's lien. If any such lien attaches or a Party receives notice of any such lien, the Party whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such lien shall cause such lien to be released and removed of record within fifteen (15) days of such attachment or notice, unless (a) such Party (i) in good faith contests or disputes the claim or claims of the lienholders and the validity of such liens, (ii) promptly commences legal action to remove such lien and (iii) furnishes to the other Party a bond or other acceptable security in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested liens and (b) during such period the lienholders' proceedings are stayed. 3.13 Books and Records. Each Party shall maintain books and records pertaining to Delivered Energy, maintenance and repair of the Shared Substation Facilities and its other activities with respect to the Shared Substation Facilities under and pursuant to this Agreement, and make, within a reasonable timeframe, such books and records available during regular business hours to the other Party requesting such information. Article 4
REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES 4.1 Representations and Warranties. As a material inducement to execution of this Agreement, each Party hereby represents and warrants to the other Party that, as of the Effective Date: 4.1.1 It is duly organized, validly existing and in good standing under the laws of the jurisdiction of its formation, and is qualified to conduct its business in all jurisdictions necessary to perform its obligations hereunder; 4.1.2 The execution, delivery and performance of this Agreement are within its powers, have been duly authorized by all necessary action and do not violate any of the terms or conditions in its governing documents or any Agreement to which it is a party, or any Requirements of Law applicable to such Party; and 4.1.3 This Agreement constitutes a legal, valid and binding obligation of such Party, enforceable against it in accordance with its terms, subject to bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization and other laws affecting creditor's rights generally, and with regard to equitable remedies, to the discretion of the court before which proceedings to obtain same may be pending. 4.2 No Other Representations and Warranties. Each Party acknowledges that it has entered into this Agreement in reliance upon only the representations and warranties set forth in this Agreement, and that no other representations or warranties have been made by the other Party with respect to the subject matter hereof. Article 5
EVENT OF DEFAULT AND REMEDIES; TERMINATION 5.1 Event of Default. The following occurrences shall constitute an event of default (each, an "Event of Default"): failure by a Party to perform any material obligation hereunder and such failure is not remedied within thirty (30) days after receipt by the defaulting Party of written notice of such failure; provided that, upon the other Party's receipt of the written request of the defaulting Party within such 30-day period, such period shall be extended once by an additional ninety (90) days for the purpose of allowing the defaulting Party to take such actions as may be necessary to diligently cure such failure and as long as (a) such default can reasonably be expected, given the actions or proposed actions of the defaulting Party, to be cured within such additional 90-day period and (b) the defaulting Party commences such cure prior to or promptly upon sending such extension request and is at all times thereafter diligently proceeding to cure such failure. 5.2 Termination. If an Event of Default occurs and is not cured within the applicable cure period set forth in Section 5.1, then the Party not in default shall, in addition to any other rights and remedies provided by law, have a continuing right, until such Event of Default is cured, at its sole discretion, to suspend performance hereof, or to terminate this Agreement upon written notice to the Party in default. 5.3 Specific Performance. Each Party shall be entitled to seek and obtain a decree compelling specific performance or granting injunctive relief with respect to, and shall be entitled, without the necessity of filing any bond, to enjoin any actual or threatened breach of any material obligation of the other Party under this Agreement. The Parties agree that specific performance (including temporary and preliminary relief) and injunctive relief are proper in the event of any actual or threatened breach of any material obligation of the other Party under this Agreement, and that any liability limits contained in this Agreement shall not operate to limit the exercise of each Party's remedies in equity to cause the other Party to perform its obligations under this Agreement. In any action for specific performance or injunctive relief, all expenses incurred by the prevailing Party in such proceeding, including, but not limited to, reasonable counsel fees, shall be awarded to the prevailing Party in such proceeding. 5.4 Limitations of Remedies, Liability and Damages. The Parties agree that the remedies and measures of damages provided in this Agreement satisfy the essential purposes hereof. If no measure of damages or other remedy is expressly provided herein, the obligor's liability shall be limited to direct actual damages only, which direct actual damages shall be the sole and exclusive remedy and all other remedies or damages at law or in equity are waived. Except as otherwise expressly provided herein, neither Party shall be liable for consequential, incidental, punitive, exemplary or indirect damages, lost profits or other business interruption damages, whether such damages are allowed or provided by statute, in tort, under this Agreement, under any indemnity provision or otherwise. FOR THE AVOIDANCE OF DOUBT, LOST REVENUES (INCLUDING GROSSED UP PRODUCTION TAX CREDITS) FROM LOST PRODUCTION RESULTING FROM AN OUTAGE, DISCONNECTION, OR DAMAGE TO THE FACILITIES, SHALL NOT BE CONSIDERED CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES HEREUNDER, AND SHALL BE FULLY RECOVERABLE DAMAGES FOR ANY CLAIMS ARISING HEREUNDER, INCLUDING THIRD PARTY CLAIMS FOR INDEMNIFICATION UNDER SECTION 7.4 OR CLAIMS FOR AMOUNTS DUE UNDER SECTIONS 3.1, 3.3, or 3.7.2, IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE TERMS OF SUCH PROVISIONS. Article 6
ASSIGNMENT 6.1 Assignment. Neither Party shall assign this Agreement or any of its rights or obligations hereunder without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld or delayed. Any attempted assignment that violates this Section 6.1 shall be voidable, at the option of the non-assigning Party. In the event of a sale or other transfer by a Party of its Facility, such Party shall require, as a condition to the sale or other transfer, that the party acquiring the Facility shall sign a counterpart to this Agreement, agreeing to be bound by the terms hereof and assuming the obligations of the selling or transferring party hereunder. Notwithstanding the foregoing, either Party may collaterally assign this Agreement to parties providing financing for its Facility without the prior consent of the other Party. 6.2 Binding Effect. This Agreement shall inure to the benefit of and be binding upon the Parties and their respective successors and permitted assigns. Article 7
FORCE MAJEURE; INDEMNITY 7.1 Force Majeure Event. As used in this Agreement, a "Force Majeure Event" shall mean causes or events beyond the reasonable control of, and without the fault or negligence of the Party claiming a Force Majeure Event, including, to the extent any of the following satisfy the foregoing, acts of God, sudden actions of the elements such as floods, earthquakes, hurricanes, or tornadoes; high winds of sufficient strength or duration to materially damage a facility or significantly impair its operation; lightning; fire; ice storms; sabotage; vandalism beyond that which could reasonably be prevented by Ironwood or Westar; terrorism; war; riots; explosion; blockades; insurrection; strike; slow down or labor disruptions (even if such difficulties could be resolved by conceding to the demands of a labor group); actions or inactions by any governmental authority taken after the date hereof (including the adoption or change in any rule or regulation or environmental constraints lawfully imposed by such governmental authority) but only if such requirements, actions, or failures to act prevent or delay performance; and inability, despite due diligence, to obtain any licenses, permits, or approvals required by any governmental authority. A Force Majeure Event does not include (i) an act of negligence or wrongdoing; (ii) events arising from the failure by a Party to operate and maintain the Shared Substation Facilities or its own facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practices and the standards set forth in this Agreement; (iii) equipment failures, except to the extent caused by a Force Majeure Event; (iv) an increase in the variable and fixed costs of operation and maintenance of the Shared Substation Facilities; (iv) failure of third parties to provide goods or services essential to a Party's performance, unless such failure is caused by a Force Majeure Event; (v) delays in or an inability of a Party hereto to obtain financing, or (vi) economic hardship. 7.2 Burden of Proof. The Party claiming a Force Majeure Event shall have the burden of proof as to whether such Force Majeure Event (a) has occurred, (b) was not a result of such Party's fault or negligence, and (c) could not have been avoided by due diligence or the use of best efforts of such Party. 7.3 Excused Performance. Each Party shall be excused from performance and shall not be considered to be in default with respect to any obligation hereunder, if and to the extent, that its failure of, or delay in, performance is due to a Force Majeure Event, except as expressly provided otherwise in this Agreement in the case of the obligation to pay money in a timely manner for services actually performed or other liabilities actually incurred, provided that: 7.3.1 such Party gives the other Party written notice describing the particulars of the Force Majeure Event as soon as is reasonably practicable; 7.3.2 the suspension of performance is of no greater scope and of no longer duration than is reasonably required by the Force Majeure Event; 7.3.3 no obligations of the Party which arose before the occurrence causing the suspension of performance are excused as a result of the occurrence; 7.3.4 the Party uses commercially reasonable efforts to overcome or mitigate the effects of such occurrence; and 7.3.5 when the Party is able to resume performance of its obligations under this Agreement, such Party shall give the other Party written notice to that effect and shall promptly resume performance hereunder. 7.4 Indemnification. 7.4.1 Each Party (the "Indemnifying Party") agrees to indemnify, hold harmless and defend, as set forth in Section 7.4.2, the other Party, its affiliates and its and their respective officers, directors, shareholders, members, partners, and employees and the successors and assigns of all of the foregoing (each, an "Indemnified Party") from and against all Losses sustained or incurred by an Indemnified Party to the extent the Losses arise out of personal injury or death to natural persons or physical damage to tangible property of any Person caused by (a) an Event of Default under this Agreement, (b) violation of any applicable Requirements of Law, or (c) the negligent or tortious acts, errors or omissions of the Indemnifying Party, its affiliates, or its and their respective officers, directors, shareholders, members, partners or employees. Nothing in this Section 7.4 shall enlarge or relieve Ironwood or Westar of any liability to the other for any breach of this Agreement or for any event or occurrence for which any other remedy is specified hereunder. This indemnification obligation shall apply notwithstanding any negligent or intentional acts, errors or omissions of the Indemnified Party, but the Indemnifying Party's liability to pay damages to the Indemnified Party shall be reduced in proportion to the percentage by which the Indemnified Party's negligent or intentional acts, errors or omissions caused the damages. Neither Party shall be indemnified for its damages resulting from its sole negligence, intentional acts or willful misconduct. These indemnity provisions shall not be construed to relieve any insurer of its obligation to pay claims consistent with the provisions of a valid insurance policy. 7.4.2 Promptly after receipt by a Party of any claim or notice of the commencement of any action, administrative, or legal proceeding, or investigation as to which the indemnity provided for in this Section 7.4 may apply, the Indemnified Party shall notify the Indemnifying Party in writing of such fact. The Indemnifying Party shall assume the defense thereof with counsel designated by such Party and satisfactory to the Indemnified Party, provided, however, that if the defendants in any such action include both the Indemnified Party and the Indemnifying Party and the Indemnified Party shall have reasonably concluded that there may be legal defenses available to it which are different from or additional to, or inconsistent with, those available to the Indemnifying Party, the Indemnified Party shall have the right to select and be represented by separate counsel, at the Indemnifying Party's expense, unless a liability insurer is willing to pay such costs. 7.4.3 If the Indemnifying Party fails to assume the defense of a claim meriting indemnification, the Indemnified Party may at the expense of the Indemnifying Party contest, settle, or pay such claim, provided that settlement or full payment of any such claim may be made only following consent of the Indemnifying Party or, absent such consent, written opinion of the Indemnified Party's counsel that such claim is meritorious or warrants settlement. 7.4.4 Except as otherwise provided in this Section 7.4, in the event that a Party is obligated to indemnify and hold the other Party and its successors and assigns harmless under this Section 7.4, the amount owing to the Indemnified Party will be the amount of the Indemnified Party's actual Loss net of any insurance proceeds received by the Indemnified Party following a reasonable effort by the Indemnified Party to obtain such insurance proceeds. Article 8
NOTICES AND ADDRESS FOR PAYMENT 8.1 Notices. Notices required by this Agreement shall be addressed to the other Party, including the other Party's Authorized Representative and Alternate, at the addresses noted below as either Party updates them from time to time by written notice to the other Party. Any notice, request, consent, or other communication required or authorized under this Agreement to be given by one Party to the other Party shall be in writing. It shall either be hand delivered or mailed, postage prepaid, to the representative of said other Party. If mailed, the notice, request, consent or other communication shall be simultaneously sent by facsimile or other electronic means. Article 9
MISCELLANEOUS 9.1 Disputes. In the event of any dispute arising under this Agreement (a "Dispute"), within ten (10) days following the delivered date of a written request by either Party (a "Dispute Notice"), (i) each Party shall appoint a representative (individually, a "Party Representative", together, the "Parties' Representatives"), and (ii) the Parties' Representatives shall meet, negotiate and attempt in good faith to resolve the Dispute quickly, informally and inexpensively. In the event the Parties' Representatives cannot resolve the Dispute within thirty (30) days after commencement of negotiations, within ten (10) days following any request by either Party at any time thereafter, each Party Representative (A) shall independently prepare a written summary of the Dispute describing the issues and claims, (B) shall exchange its summary with the summary of the Dispute prepared by the other Party Representative, and (C) shall submit a copy of both summaries to a senior officer of the Party Representative's Party with authority to irrevocably bind the Party to a resolution of the Dispute. Within ten (10) Business Days after receipt of the Dispute summaries, the senior officers for both Parties shall negotiate in good faith to resolve the Dispute. If the Parties are unable to resolve the Dispute within fourteen (14) days following receipt of the Dispute summaries by the senior officers, either Party may initiate procedures seeking available legal remedies pursuant to Section 9.2. Notwithstanding the existence of a Dispute, each Party shall continue during the pendency of such Dispute to fulfill its obligations in accordance with the terms hereof; provided, that this obligation shall not apply after the termination of this Agreement. 9.2 Applicable Law; Jurisdiction. THIS AGREEMENT SHALL BE GOVERNED BY AND INTERPRETED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE LAWS OF THE STATE OF KANSAS, WITHOUT REGARD TO ITS CONFLICTS OF LAW PRINCIPLES. EACH PARTY WAIVES ITS RESPECTIVE RIGHTS TO ANY JURY TRIAL WITH RESPECT TO ANY LITIGATION ARISING UNDER OR IN CONNECTION WITH THIS AGREEMENT. ANY PROCEEDING IN CONNECTION WITH ANY CLAIM, COUNTERCLAIM, DEMAND, CAUSE OF ACTION, DISPUTE AND CONTROVERSY ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS AGREEMENT, THE PARTIES HEREBY CONSENT TO THE EXCLUSIVE JURISDICTION OF THE FEDERAL AND STATE COURTS SITTING IN KANSAS CITY, KANSAS. 9.3 Binding Effect. This Agreement, as it may be amended from time to time pursuant to this Article 9, shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the Parties hereto and their respective successors in interest, legal representatives, and assigns permitted hereunder. 9.4 Complete Agreement; Amendments. The terms and provisions contained in this Agreement constitute the entire agreement between Westar and Ironwood with respect to shared use of the Shared Substation Facilities and shall supersede all previous communications, representations, or agreements, either verbal or written, between Westar and Ironwood with respect to the foregoing. This Agreement may be amended, changed, modified, or altered, provided that such amendment, change, modification, or alteration shall be in writing and signed by both Parties hereto. 9.5 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts, and each executed counterpart shall have the same force and effect as an original instrument. A signature page in "PDF" format or an electronic signature to this Agreement shall be deemed an original and binding upon the party against which enforcement is sought. 9.6 Disclaimer of Third Party Beneficiary Rights. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to create any duty to, or standard of care with reference to, or any liability to, any Person not a party to this Agreement. 9.7 Headings. Captions and headings used in this Agreement are for ease of reference only and do not constitute a part of this Agreement. 9.8 Relationship of the Parties. This Agreement shall not be interpreted to create an association, joint venture, or partnership between the Parties nor to impose any partnership obligation or liability upon either Party. Neither Party shall have any right, power, or authority to enter into any agreement or undertaking for, or act on behalf of, or to act as an agent or representative of, the other Party. 9.9 Severability. In the event any of the terms, covenants, or conditions of this Agreement, its Schedules, or the application of any such terms, covenants, or conditions, shall be held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable by any court or administrative body having jurisdiction, all other terms, covenants, and conditions of this Agreement and their application not adversely affected thereby shall remain in force and effect; provided, however, that Westar and Ironwood shall negotiate in good faith to attempt to implement an equitable adjustment in the provisions of this Agreement with a view toward effecting the purposes of this Agreement by replacing the provision that is held invalid, illegal, or unenforceable with a valid provision the economic effect of which comes as close as possible to that of the provision that has been found to be invalid, illegal or unenforceable. 9.10 Survival of Obligations. Cancellation, expiration, or earlier termination of this Agreement shall not relieve the Parties of obligations that by their nature should survive such cancellation, expiration, or termination, prior to the term of the applicable statute of limitations, including warranties, remedies, or indemnities which obligation shall survive for the period of the applicable statute(s) of limitation. 9.11 Waiver. The failure of either Party to enforce or insist upon compliance with or strict performance of any of the terms or conditions of this Agreement, or to take advantage of any of its rights thereunder, shall not constitute a waiver or relinquishment of any such terms, conditions, or rights, but the same shall be and remain at all times in full force and effect. No waiver by any Party hereto of any one or more defaults by the other Parties in the performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement shall be construed as a waiver of any other default or defaults whether of a like kind or different nature. No failure or delay by any Party hereto in exercising any right, power, privilege, or remedy hereunder shall operate as a waiver thereof. 9.12 FERC Approval. The Parties acknowledge and agree that: (a) this Agreement will be publicly available through its filing with FERC for acceptance under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act; (b) after this Agreement has been filed with FERC under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, any subsequent amendments to this Agreement must be accepted by FERC, and the effectiveness of such amendments will be contingent on such FERC acceptance; (c) any rates for service in the Agreement specified herein shall remain in effect for the term of the Agreement, and shall not be subject to change through application to the FERC pursuant to the provisions of Section 205 of the Federal Power Act absent the agreement of all Parties thereto; and (d) changes in ownership of the Shared Substation Facilities may be subject to FERC approval. Subject to the terms and conditions set forth herein, the Parties agree to execute and deliver all documents reasonably necessary for this Agreement to comply with FERC requirements. 9.13 FERC Standard of Review; Mobile-Sierra. Absent the written agreement of the Parties to the contrary, the standard of review for changes to any rate, charge, classification, term or condition of this Agreement, whether proposed by a Party (to the extent that any waiver below is unenforceable or ineffective as to such Party), a nonparty or FERC acting sua sponte, shall be the "public interest" standard of review set forth in United Gas Pipe Line Co. v. Mobile Gas Service Corp., 350 U.S. 332 (1956) and Federal Power Commission v. Sierra Pacific Power Co., 350 U.S. 348 (1956) and clarified by Morgan Stanley Capital Group, Inc. v. Public Util. Dist. No.1 of Snohomish, 554 U.S. 527, 545 (2008) (the "Mobile-Sierra" doctrine). Notwithstanding any other provision of Agreement and absent the prior written agreement of the Parties, each Party, to the fullest extent permitted by applicable law, for itself and its respective successors and permitted assigns, hereby expressly and irrevocably waives any rights it can or may have, now or in the future, whether under Sections 205, 206, or 306 of the Federal Power Act or otherwise, to seek to obtain from FERC by any means, directly or indirectly (through complaint, investigation, supporting a third party seeking to obtain or otherwise), and each hereby covenants and agrees not at any time to seek to so obtain, an order from FERC changing any provision of this Agreement specifying any rate or other material economic terms and conditions agreed to herein.

Ironwood Windpower, LLC
Tariff Volume No. 1 Ironwood Windpower, LLC Wholesale Marked-Based Rate Tariff Providing for Sales of Capacity, Energy, or Ancillary Services Tariff Volume No. 1
1. Availability. Ironwood Windpower, LLC ("Seller") makes electric energy and capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. Seller also makes available to any purchaser, the ancillary services listed below:
a. RTO/ISO Specific PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP.
b. Third Party Provider Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity and ancillary services by Seller which are subject to the jurisdiction of this Commission.
3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between Seller and the purchaser.
4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between Seller and the purchaser.
5. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority.
a. Exemptions: The Commission granted Seller in Docket No. ER12-1502-000 the following waivers and blanket authorization: (a) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations requiring the filing of cost-of-service information, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (b) waiver of Part 41 and Part 101, with the exception of 18 C.F.R. ?? 141.14 and 141.15; (c) waiver of Part 141 of the Commission's regulations concerning accounting and reporting requirements; and (d) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumption of liabilities.
b. Limitations: Seller does not have authority under this tariff to make sales within the Duke Energy Carolinas balancing authority area, the Progress Energy Carolinas balancing authority areas, or in Peninsular Florida (the "Mitigated Markets"). See Duke Power, a Div. of Duke Energy Corp., 111 FERC ? 61,506, at P 61 (2005) (limitation on market-based rate sales within the Duke Energy Carolinas balancing authority area); Florida Power Corp., 113 FERC ? 61,131, at P 17 (2005) (limitations on market-based rate sales within the Progress Energy Carolinas balancing authority areas and Peninsular Florida); see also Duke Energy Corp., 136 FERC ? 61,245 (2011); Duke Energy Corp., 139 FERC ? 61,194 (2012). Any sales by Seller within the Mitigated Markets will be made in accordance with the rate schedules approved by the Commission prior to Seller commencing such sales. Peninsular Florida is defined for purposes of this tariff as all of that portion of the State of Florida lying to the east of Florida Power Corporation's ("FPC") points of interconnection with Gulf Power Company, and to the south of the points of interconnection of those transmission lines jointly owned by Florida Power & Light Company and Jacksonville Electric Authority with Georgia Power Company and south of the points of interconnection of the City of Tallahassee and FPC with Georgia Power Company. See DeSoto County Generating Co., 106 FERC ? 61,100 (2004).
7. Modifications. Seller may unilaterally apply, under Federal Power Act section 205 and the regulations promulgated thereunder, to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this Tariff.
8. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ? 35.36(a), in the Southwest Power Pool region. Seller is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ? 35.36(a), in the Northeast, Southwest, Central, Southeast, and Northwest regions.
